esex, England","Monken Hadley, Middlesex, England":"Monken Hadley, Middlesex, England","Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England":"Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1371–8 December 1456":"1371–8 December 1456","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1371–1456":"1371–1456","1373–Male":"1373–Deceased","1376–Female":"1376–Deceased","1392–1456":"1392–1456","1394–1442":"1394–1442","1343–1391":"1343–1391","8 December 1456":"8 December 1456","1373":"1373","1394":"1394","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1369":"1369","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1343":"1343","1442":"1442","1376":"1376","16 September 1442":"16 September 1442","Hayes, Middlesex, England":"Hayes, Middlesex, England","Monken Hadley, Middlesex, England":"Monken Hadley, Middlesex, England","Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England":"Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish, English:  see  Green  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Green","meanings":["English: either a nickname for someone who was fond of dressing in this color (Old English <i>grēne</i>) or was young or immature, or who had played the part of the ‘Green Man’ in the May Day celebrations, or a topographic name for someone who lived near a village green (Middle English <i>grene</i>, a transferred use of the color term). This is one of the most common and widespread of English surnames. In North America it has assimilated cognates from other languages, notably German <b>Grün</b> (see   Gruen  ) and Dutch   Groen  ; compare 7 below. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: alternatively, from a Middle English personal name <i>Grene</i>.","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hUainín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uainín</i>’, a personal name from a pet form of <i>uaine</i> ‘green’, see   Honan  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":11,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":84,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of Y